+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01X5Ay8UboyFDnsThMe9EWud","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Beam Splitter Simulator — Design\n     2→\n     3→## Architecture\n     4→\n     5→Single file `src/index.ts` exporting two functions. All helpers are internal.\n     6→\n     7→## Core Data Structures\n     8→\n     9→```typescript\n    10→type Direction = 'down' | 'down-left' | 'down-right';\n    11→\n    12→// Delta map for each direction\n    13→const DELTAS: Record<Direction, [number, number]> = {\n    14→  'down': [1, 0],\n    15→  'down-left': [1, -1],\n    16→  'down-right': [1, 1],\n    17→};\n    18→\n    19→// A beam in flight: position + direction\n    20→interface Beam {\n    21→  row: number;\n    22→  col: number;\n    23→  dir: Direction;\n    24→}\n    25→```\n    26→\n    27→## Algorithm: countBeamCells\n    28→\n    29→Use a **splitter-graph reachability** approach to avoid exponential blowup:\n    30→\n    31→1. Find source `S` on the top row.\n    32→2. From the source (and from each reachable splitter), trace each outgoing beam direction step-by-step, collecting cells visited along the way.\n    33→3. When a beam hits a splitter, record that splitter as reachable and queue it for processing (if not already processed).\n    34→4. When a beam exits the grid, stop that trace.\n    35→5. Use a `Set<string>` of `\"row,col\"` keys to track distinct visited cells.\n    36→6. Process splitters BFS-style: each splitter emits two beams (down-left, down-right). Trace each.\n    37→\n    38→This visits at most O(splitters × grid_dimension) cells, well within performance bounds.\n    39→\n    40→## Algorithm: countBeamPaths\n    41→\n    42→Use **memoized DP on the splitter graph**:\n    43→\n    44→1. Build a directed graph where nodes are the source and each splitter.\n    45→2. From each node, trace each outgoing beam to find:\n    46→   - If it hits another splitter → edge to that splitter node\n    47→   - If it exits the grid → leaf (contributes 1 path)\n    48→   - If it goes out of bounds before hitting anything → leaf (contributes 1 path)\n    49→3. `pathCount(node)` = sum of `pathCount(child)` for each outgoing edge, plus count of exits.\n    50→4. Memoize results per node. With ≤50 splitters, this is O(50) nodes max.\n    51→5. Use `bigint` throughout since results can be 2^50+.\n    52→\n    53→Key insight: a beam that exits the grid IS a complete path (absorbed = path ends = counts as a path).\n    54→\n    55→## Edge Cases\n    56→\n    57→- No splitters: beam goes straight down, 1 path, cells = rows visited.\n    58→- Beam exits sideways (col < 0 or col >= cols): still a complete path.\n    59→- Multiple beams hit same splitter from different directions: each produces its own pair of outgoing beams, but for path counting we memoize per (splitter, incoming_direction) — actually since splitters always split the same way regardless of direction, we can just track which splitter is reached and from which direction, since the outgoing beams are always down-left and down-right.\n    60→- Wait — re-reading the spec: splitters always produce down-left and down-right regardless of incoming direction. So a splitter node always has the same two outgoing beams. The path count from a splitter is always the same regardless of how you arrived. So we can memoize by splitter position alone.\n    61→\n    62→## Function Signatures\n    63→\n    64→```typescript\n    65→export function countBeamCells(grid: string[][]): number;\n    66→export function countBeamPaths(grid: string[][]): bigint;\n    67→```\n    68→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"24f7b93c-c8fa-4019-aa98-2a8ec9610204","uuid":"688f4341-a0b5-466c-af20-3899bc8f72a3","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/plans/2026-03-06-beam-splitter-design.md","content":"# Beam Splitter Simulator — Design\n\n## Architecture\n\nSingle file `src/index.ts` exporting two functions. All helpers are internal.\n\n## Core Data Structures\n\n```typescript\ntype Direction = 'down' | 'down-left' | 'down-right';\n\n// Delta map for each direction\nconst DELTAS: Record<Direction, [number, number]> = {\n  'down': [1, 0],\n  'down-left': [1, -1],\n  'down-right': [1, 1],\n};\n\n// A beam in flight: position + direction\ninterface Beam {\n  row: number;\n  col: number;\n  dir: Direction;\n}\n```\n\n## Algorithm: countBeamCells\n\nUse a **splitter-graph reachability** approach to avoid exponential blowup:\n\n1. Find source `S` on the top row.\n2. From the source (and from each reachable splitter), trace each outgoing beam direction step-by-step, collecting cells visited along the way.\n3. When a beam hits a splitter, record that splitter as reachable and queue it for processing (if not already processed).\n4. When a beam exits the grid, stop that trace.\n5. Use a `Set<string>` of `\"row,col\"` keys to track distinct visited cells.\n6. Process splitters BFS-style: each splitter emits two beams (down-left, down-right). Trace each.\n\nThis visits at most O(splitters × grid_dimension) cells, well within performance bounds.\n\n## Algorithm: countBeamPaths\n\nUse **memoized DP on the splitter graph**:\n\n1. Build a directed graph where nodes are the source and each splitter.\n2. From each node, trace each outgoing beam to find:\n   - If it hits another splitter → edge to that splitter node\n   - If it exits the grid → leaf (contributes 1 path)\n   - If it goes out of bounds before hitting anything → leaf (contributes 1 path)\n3. `pathCount(node)` = sum of `pathCount(child)` for each outgoing edge, plus count of exits.\n4. Memoize results per node. With ≤50 splitters, this is O(50) nodes max.\n5. Use `bigint` throughout since results can be 2^50+.\n\nKey insight: a beam that exits the grid IS a complete path (absorbed = path ends = counts as a path).\n\n## Edge Cases\n\n- No splitters: beam goes straight down, 1 path, cells = rows visited.\n- Beam exits sideways (col < 0 or col >= cols): still a complete path.\n- Multiple beams hit same splitter from different directions: each produces its own pair of outgoing beams, but for path counting we memoize per (splitter, incoming_direction) — actually since splitters always split the same way regardless of direction, we can just track which splitter is reached and from which direction, since the outgoing beams are always down-left and down-right.\n- Wait — re-reading the spec: splitters always produce down-left and down-right regardless of incoming direction. So a splitter node always has the same two outgoing beams. The path count from a splitter is always the same regardless of how you arrived. So we can memoize by splitter position alone.\n\n## Function Signatures\n\n```typescript\nexport function countBeamCells(grid: string[][]): number;\nexport function countBeamPaths(grid: string[][]): bigint;\n```\n","numLines":68,"startLine":1,"totalLines":68}}}
