+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01ASJtabpu5P6gPLQ2Mdj2yi","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Beam Splitter\n     2→\n     3→Build a beam propagation simulator for a 2D grid laboratory.\n     4→\n     5→## Grid Format\n     6→\n     7→The grid is a 2D array of single-character strings:\n     8→\n     9→- `'S'` — beam source (always on the top row). Emits a beam straight down.\n    10→- `'^'` — splitter. When a beam arrives, it splits into two diagonal beams.\n    11→- `'.'` — empty cell. Beams pass through.\n    12→\n    13→Beams that leave the grid boundaries are absorbed (they stop).\n    14→\n    15→## Beam Movement Rules\n    16→\n    17→1. A beam from the source `'S'` moves **straight down** (row+1, same column) each step.\n    18→2. When a beam hits a splitter `'^'`, it splits into **two beams**:\n    19→   - One goes **down-left** (row+1, col-1)\n    20→   - One goes **down-right** (row+1, col+1)\n    21→   The original beam is consumed by the splitter (it does not continue straight).\n    22→3. An unsplit beam (not at a splitter) continues in its current direction:\n    23→   - A downward beam continues downward (row+1, same col)\n    24→   - A down-left beam continues down-left (row+1, col-1)\n    25→   - A down-right beam continues down-right (row+1, col+1)\n    26→4. A beam is **absorbed** when it moves outside the grid boundaries (row < 0, row >= rows, col < 0, col >= cols).\n    27→5. Multiple beams can occupy the same cell simultaneously.\n    28→6. Splitters always split regardless of the beam's incoming direction.\n    29→\n    30→## API\n    31→\n    32→Export two functions from `src/index.ts`:\n    33→\n    34→### `countBeamCells(grid: string[][]): number`\n    35→\n    36→Count the number of distinct cells visited by any beam. A cell counts once even if multiple beams pass through it. The source cell `'S'` counts as visited. Splitter cells hit by beams count as visited.\n    37→\n    38→### `countBeamPaths(grid: string[][]): bigint`\n    39→\n    40→Count the total number of distinct source-to-exit paths through the grid. Each time a beam splits at `'^'`, both branches are separate paths. A path ends when the beam exits the grid (moves beyond any edge).\n    41→\n    42→With K splitters along a beam's path, there are potentially 2^K paths. The result can be astronomically large, so return a `bigint`.\n    43→\n    44→**Performance constraint**: Must handle a 200x200 grid with up to 50 splitters and return results in under 5 seconds. Enumerating individual paths is not feasible for large inputs.\n    45→\n    46→## Example\n    47→\n    48→```\n    49→Grid (4 rows x 5 cols):\n    50→. S . . .\n    51→. . . . .\n    52→. ^ . . .\n    53→. . . . .\n    54→```\n    55→\n    56→- The beam starts at (0,1) where `'S'` is.\n    57→- It moves down: (1,1), (2,1) — hits splitter.\n    58→- Splits into down-left (3,0) and down-right (3,2).\n    59→- Both beams exit the grid after row 3.\n    60→- Visited cells: (0,1), (1,1), (2,1), (3,0), (3,2) → `countBeamCells` returns **5**.\n    61→- Paths: 2 distinct paths (one ending at (3,0), one at (3,2)) → `countBeamPaths` returns **2n**.\n    62→\n    63→```\n    64→Grid with two splitters:\n    65→. S . . .\n    66→. ^ . . .\n    67→^ . ^ . .\n    68→. . . . .\n    69→```\n    70→\n    71→- Beam starts at (0,1), moves to (1,1) — hits splitter.\n    72→- Splits: down-left to (2,0) hits another splitter, down-right to (2,2) hits another splitter.\n    73→- (2,0) splitter: sends beams to (3,-1) absorbed and (3,1).\n    74→- (2,2) splitter: sends beams to (3,1) and (3,3).\n    75→- `countBeamCells`: (0,1), (1,1), (2,0), (2,2), (3,1), (3,3) → **6** (note: two beams land on (3,1) but it counts once).\n    76→- `countBeamPaths`: 4 paths total, but one is absorbed → **3n** paths that exit through the bottom or sides at valid cells... Actually, all 4 paths exit (absorbed = exits grid): paths to (3,-1), (3,1), (3,1), (3,3) → **4n**.\n    77→\n    78→## Commands\n    79→\n    80→```bash\n    81→npm test        # run tests\n    82→npm run build   # compile TypeScript\n    83→npm run lint    # lint source\n    84→```\n    85→\n    86→## File Structure\n    87→\n    88→Place your implementation in `src/`. The main entry point should be `src/index.ts`.\n    89→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"24f7b93c-c8fa-4019-aa98-2a8ec9610204","uuid":"acd3fc1f-5d93-4437-96b1-9c25c5d2e80c","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/TASK.md","content":"# Beam Splitter\n\nBuild a beam propagation simulator for a 2D grid laboratory.\n\n## Grid Format\n\nThe grid is a 2D array of single-character strings:\n\n- `'S'` — beam source (always on the top row). Emits a beam straight down.\n- `'^'` — splitter. When a beam arrives, it splits into two diagonal beams.\n- `'.'` — empty cell. Beams pass through.\n\nBeams that leave the grid boundaries are absorbed (they stop).\n\n## Beam Movement Rules\n\n1. A beam from the source `'S'` moves **straight down** (row+1, same column) each step.\n2. When a beam hits a splitter `'^'`, it splits into **two beams**:\n   - One goes **down-left** (row+1, col-1)\n   - One goes **down-right** (row+1, col+1)\n   The original beam is consumed by the splitter (it does not continue straight).\n3. An unsplit beam (not at a splitter) continues in its current direction:\n   - A downward beam continues downward (row+1, same col)\n   - A down-left beam continues down-left (row+1, col-1)\n   - A down-right beam continues down-right (row+1, col+1)\n4. A beam is **absorbed** when it moves outside the grid boundaries (row < 0, row >= rows, col < 0, col >= cols).\n5. Multiple beams can occupy the same cell simultaneously.\n6. Splitters always split regardless of the beam's incoming direction.\n\n## API\n\nExport two functions from `src/index.ts`:\n\n### `countBeamCells(grid: string[][]): number`\n\nCount the number of distinct cells visited by any beam. A cell counts once even if multiple beams pass through it. The source cell `'S'` counts as visited. Splitter cells hit by beams count as visited.\n\n### `countBeamPaths(grid: string[][]): bigint`\n\nCount the total number of distinct source-to-exit paths through the grid. Each time a beam splits at `'^'`, both branches are separate paths. A path ends when the beam exits the grid (moves beyond any edge).\n\nWith K splitters along a beam's path, there are potentially 2^K paths. The result can be astronomically large, so return a `bigint`.\n\n**Performance constraint**: Must handle a 200x200 grid with up to 50 splitters and return results in under 5 seconds. Enumerating individual paths is not feasible for large inputs.\n\n## Example\n\n```\nGrid (4 rows x 5 cols):\n. S . . .\n. . . . .\n. ^ . . .\n. . . . .\n```\n\n- The beam starts at (0,1) where `'S'` is.\n- It moves down: (1,1), (2,1) — hits splitter.\n- Splits into down-left (3,0) and down-right (3,2).\n- Both beams exit the grid after row 3.\n- Visited cells: (0,1), (1,1), (2,1), (3,0), (3,2) → `countBeamCells` returns **5**.\n- Paths: 2 distinct paths (one ending at (3,0), one at (3,2)) → `countBeamPaths` returns **2n**.\n\n```\nGrid with two splitters:\n. S . . .\n. ^ . . .\n^ . ^ . .\n. . . . .\n```\n\n- Beam starts at (0,1), moves to (1,1) — hits splitter.\n- Splits: down-left to (2,0) hits another splitter, down-right to (2,2) hits another splitter.\n- (2,0) splitter: sends beams to (3,-1) absorbed and (3,1).\n- (2,2) splitter: sends beams to (3,1) and (3,3).\n- `countBeamCells`: (0,1), (1,1), (2,0), (2,2), (3,1), (3,3) → **6** (note: two beams land on (3,1) but it counts once).\n- `countBeamPaths`: 4 paths total, but one is absorbed → **3n** paths that exit through the bottom or sides at valid cells... Actually, all 4 paths exit (absorbed = exits grid): paths to (3,-1), (3,1), (3,1), (3,3) → **4n**.\n\n## Commands\n\n```bash\nnpm test        # run tests\nnpm run build   # compile TypeScript\nnpm run lint    # lint source\n```\n\n## File Structure\n\nPlace your implementation in `src/`. The main entry point should be `src/index.ts`.\n","numLines":89,"startLine":1,"totalLines":89}}}
